y &= \fx \\ \therefore x &= \frac{1}{3} \left[\sqrt{y + 6} - 1 \right] \\ \implies f^{-1}(x) &= \invfx \\ \text{Hence }f^{-1}(43) &= 2\text{ and } f^{-1}(163) = 4 \end{align} %text
\incorrect % \begin{align}
y &= \fx \\ \therefore x &= \frac{1}{3} \left[\sqrt{y + 9} - 2 \right] \\ \implies f^{-1}(x) &= \dfrac{\sqrt{x+9} - 2}{3} \\ \text{Hence }f^{-1}(43) &= \dfrac{\sqrt{52}-2}{3}\\ \text{ and } f^{-1}(163) &= \dfrac{\sqrt{172}-2}{3} \end{align} %text %

reason.tex:
%text If $f:\N\to S$, then $f^{-1}:S\to\N$. Which means, that the output of $f^{-1}(x)$ will be a natural number That said, % \begin{align}
y &= \fx = \left\lbrace (3x+1)^2 - 1\right\rbrace -5 \\ &= (3x+1)^2 - 6 \\ \therefore x &= \dfrac{\sqrt{y+6}-1}{3} \end{align} %text In the last equation, we evaluate $x$ in terms of $y$. Hence, $x$ is the \underline\text{dependent} variable and $y$ is the \underline\text{independent} variable And by convention, we use $x$ for independent and $y$ for dependent variables Hence, \[ x = \frac{\sqrt{y+6}-1}{3} \implies f^{-1}(x) = \frac{\sqrt{x+6}-1}{3} \] And therefore, % \begin{align}
f^{-1}(43) &= \frac{\sqrt{43+6}-1}{3} = 2 \\ f^{-1}(163) &= \frac{\sqrt{163+6}-1}{3} = 4 \end{align} %text %
